      <div class="ians-column">
        <h2 class="oj-pt0-important">Introduction</h2>
        <p>
        This section covers the regulatory requirements for practical training
        instructors. It provides information on the regulations that apply to
        the training and assessments of ATCOs and practical instructors.
        Although we will mainly focus on the <strong>European</strong>
        regulatory, operational and organisational environment, there have been
        some recent changes to ICAO documents that have introduced OJTI
        requirements and an OJTI <strong>competency framework</strong>. 
      </p>

      </div>

      <div class="oj-hero"></div>

      <div class="ians-column">

        <p>In Europe, the <strong>requirement</strong> to have an OJTI
        <strong>endorsement</strong> in your ATC <strong>licence</strong> before
        providing operational (live) training was established more than 20 years
        ago and is supported with the development of <strong>OJTI training and
          refresher courses</strong>. The importance of these requirements,
        initially articulated through the different regulatory phases and
        organisations, has been recognised by the <strong>European
          Commission</strong> and is embedded into the so-called <strong>Basic
          Regulation</strong>, initially introduced in 2006 and updated in 2018:
        <i>Regulation (EU) 2018/1139 <a
            href="https://www.easa.europa.eu/document-library/regulations/regulation-eu-20181139"
            target="_blank">Basic regulation - Essential requirements for
            ATM/ANS and air traffic controllers</a>
          </i>. Please note that links provided here are only for information and you do not need to follow them to complete the course.
      </p>

        <p>
          <strong>This is the section that deals with the qualification of instructors:</strong>
        </p>

      </div>

      <div class=" oj-paper-torn-container">

        <div class="ians-column-wide-1 oj-paper-torn">

          <ol class="list-inside oj-reg-list-decimal">
            <li>4.7.2. Instruction on practical skills shall be given by
            appropriately qualified instructors, who have the following
            qualifications:</li>
            <ul class="list-inside oj-reg-list-alpha">
              <li>(a) meet the theoretical knowledge and the experience
              requirements appropriate to the instruction being given;</li>
              <li>(b) have demonstrated the ability to instruct and to use
              appropriate instructional techniques</li>
              <li>(c) have practised instructional techniques in those procedures
              in which it is intended to provide instruction; and</li>
              <li>(d) receive regular refresher training to ensure that the
              instructional competences are maintained up to date.</li>
            </ul>
            <li>4.7.3. Instructors on practical skills shall also be or have been
            entitled to act as an air traffic controller.</li>
          </ol>

        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="ians-column"></div>
      <div class="ians-column-wide-2 ians-grid-2">

        <p class=" mt-0">You will notice that according to the last requirement
        (<strong>4.7.3</strong>), instructors who are teaching practical skills
        <strong>shall be air traffic controllers</strong>, which many would
        consider as <strong>common sense</strong> (can you imagine a driving
        instructor who has never driven a car?!). Clearly, these higher-level
        rule-makers wanted to prevent the practice of using instructors with no
        ATCO background in practical ATC training.
      <br/><br/>This regulation served as a starting point for the development of more
        <strong>detailed</strong> Commission Regulation (EU) 2015/340 on ATCO
        Licensing (<i>COMMISSION REGULATION (EU) 2015/340: <a
            href="https://www.easa.europa.eu/document-library/easy-access-rules/easy-access-rules-air-traffic-controllers-licensing-and"
            target="_blank">ATCO Licensing Regulation</a>
          </i>) where most of the requirements related to ATCO practical training
        sit.
      </p>

